import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

import BlogContent from "../../components/BlogContent.astro";
---

<Layout>
	<main>
		<BlogContent title="All about Dogs" date = "November 17, 2025">
			<h2>The Enduring Bond Between Humans and Dogs</h2>
			<figure>
				<img src = "/images/dog1.jpg" alt = "dog one">
				<figcaption> Muscle, mischief, and endless love: meet the Staffy. </figcaption>
			</figure>
			<p>
				Dogs have been called “man’s best friend” for a reason. For thousands of years, they’ve shared 
				our homes, our work, and our hearts, becoming loyal companions in ways no other animal has. Their 
				mix of devotion, intelligence, and playful spirit makes them some of the most beloved animals on the planet.
			</p>
			<h2>A Long History Together</h2>
			<p>
				Dogs were domesticated from wolves around 15,000 years ago, though some evidence suggests it could have been even 
				earlier. Early humans and wolves formed a mutually beneficial relationship: humans provided food and shelter, while 
				wolves helped with hunting and offered protection. Over generations, this bond evolved into the vast array of dog 
				breeds we see today, each with unique traits suited to specific roles, from herding livestock to companionship.
			</p>
			<h2> Why Dogs Captivate Us </h2>
			<p>
				Dogs are remarkable for their emotional intelligence. They can sense human moods, respond to our gestures, and form deep 
				attachments to their families. Their loyalty is unmatched; they often recognize and respond to even subtle signs of distress 
				in their humans, offering comfort and companionship when it’s needed most. <br><br>

				Dogs also bring joy through their playful energy. Whether it’s fetching a ball, running at full speed, or simply wagging their tails 
				at the sight of you, their enthusiasm is contagious.
			</p>
			<h2>Health and Care</h2>
			<p>
				Caring for a dog goes beyond food and water. Regular exercise, veterinary care, mental stimulation, and socialization are crucial. Different 
				breeds have different needs—high-energy dogs require more playtime and activity, while smaller or older dogs may benefit from gentler routines. 
				Training and positive reinforcement help dogs thrive and reduce behavioral problems.
			</p>
			<h2>The Joy They Bring</h2>
			<p>
				Dogs teach us patience, empathy, and unconditional love. Their unwavering loyalty, joyful spirit, and ability to live fully in the moment remind 
				us to appreciate life’s simple pleasures. Whether guiding the visually impaired, providing therapy, or simply being a faithful companion, dogs 
				continue to enrich our lives in countless ways.
			</p>
			<figure>
				<img src = "/images/dog2.jpeg" alt = "dog two">
				<figcaption> Smart, stylish, and full of personality — the Mini Poodle way. </figcaption>
			</figure>
		</BlogContent>
	</main>
</Layout>
